":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","1666311, Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","Charlestown, Middlesex, Massachusetts, United States":"Charlestown, Middlesex, Massachusetts, United States","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hodges","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Hodge   with genitival or post-medieval <i>-s</i>. Occasionally, however, the name may be topographic for a person who lived or worked at the house of someone named <i>Hodge</i> or <i>Roger</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hodge","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hogge</i>, a rhyming pet form of   Roger  . In <i>The Canterbury Tales</i>, Chaucer's cook, ‘highte <i>Hogge</i> of Ware’, is invoked ‘Now tell on, <i>Roger</i> …’. Since Middle English spellings of the personal name are often impossible to distinguish from the nickname <i>Hog(ge)</i> ‘hog’, some early examples may be variants of   Hogg  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   John  , also used quite frequently in the English-speaking world. In Northern Ireland it is sometimes found as a variant of   Ewan ."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Twigg","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands): nickname for a thin person, from Middle English<i>twigge</i> ‘twig, shoot’. Since the word occurs only late in theOld English period and was initially confined to northern dialects, itmay be a borrowing from Old Norse."],"variants":[{"name":"Twiggs","meanings":["English: patronymic from   Twigg  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Twigg Hodges \"Captain\" was born in April 1596, in Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Humphrey Hodges, was 12 and his mother, Margaret DeTimperly, was 12. He married Mary